Yes, you can read only text values from a `multipart/form-data` request in Spring WebFlux without deserializing file content. 

Use the `Flux&lt;DataBuffer&gt;` to process the request parts one by one and extract the text values without fully loading the file content into memory.

Define a custom `PartProcessor`:
```
public class TextPartProcessor implements PartProcessor {

    private final Map&lt;String, String&gt; textValues;

    public TextPartProcessor() {
        this.textValues = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
    }

    @Override
    public Mono&lt;Void&gt; processPart(Part part) {
        if (part instanceof FilePart) {
            // Ignore file parts
            return Mono.empty();
        } else if (part instanceof FormFieldPart) {
            FormFieldPart formFieldPart = (FormFieldPart) part;
            textValues.put(formFieldPart.name(), formFieldPart.value());
        }
        return Mono.empty();
    }

    public Map&lt;String, String&gt; getTextValues() {
        return textValues;
    }
}

```

The controller processes the `ServerWebExchange` to extract the text values:
```
@PostMapping(&quot;/test&quot;)
public Mono&lt;ResponseEntity&lt;Map&lt;String, String&gt;&gt;&gt; handleRequest(ServerWebExchange exchange) {
    TextPartProcessor textPartProcessor = new TextPartProcessor();

    return exchange.getMultipartResolver()
            .resolveMultipart(exchange)
            .flatMapMany(multipart -&gt; Flux.fromIterable(multipart.getParts()))
            .concatMap(part -&gt; part.content().concatMap(dataBuffer -&gt; textPartProcessor.processPart(part)))
            .then(Mono.just(ResponseEntity.ok(textPartProcessor.getTextValues())));
}

```

This will process the request parts and store only the text values in the `TextPartProcessor` instance. File parts are ignored, and their content is not deserialized, which should help you avoid exceeding the default buffer capacity.

